{"type":"tool_call","subtype":"completed","call_id":"tool_bac50dec-224b-467c-843e-246da169f22","tool_call":{"mcpToolCall":{"args":{"name":"context7-query-docs","args":{"libraryId":"/websites/zod_dev_v4","query":"z.object strict unknown keys z.email string min max"},"toolCallId":"tool_bac50dec-224b-467c-843e-246da169f22","providerIdentifier":"context7","toolName":"query-docs","smartModeApprovalOnly":false,"skipApproval":false},"result":{"success":{"content":[{"text":{"text":"### Deprecated and Recommended String Format API Usage\n\nSource: https://zod.dev/v4/changelog?id=deprecates-strip\n\nCompares the deprecated method form `z.string().email()` with the recommended top-level `z.email()` API for string format validation.\n\n```javascript\nz.string().email(); // ❌ deprecated\nz.email(); // ✅ \n```\n\n--------------------------------\n\n### z.email() with Custom Regex Pattern\n\nSource: https://zod.dev/v4?id=7x-faster-array-parsing\n\nExtends the \"z.email()\" schema to support custom regular expressions for email validation, allowing for more flexible or strict validation rules.\n\n```APIDOC\n## `z.email(options)`\n\n### Description\nThe `z.email()` API now supports a custom regular expression for email validation via the `pattern` option. This allows developers to choose different levels of strictness for email validation beyond Zod's default.\n\n### Method Signature\n`z.email(options?: { pattern?: ZodRegex })`\n\n### Parameters\n- **pattern** (`ZodRegex`) - Optional - A custom regular expression schema to use for email validation. Zod exports common regexes like `z.regexes.html5Email`, `z.regexes.rfc5322Email`, and `z.regexes.unicodeEmail`.\n\n### Example Usage\n```typescript\nimport { z } from \"zod\";\n\n// Zod's default email regex (Gmail rules)\nconst defaultEmailSchema = z.email();\n\n// Using the HTML5 email regex\nconst html5EmailSchema = z.email({ pattern: z.regexes.html5Email });\n\n// Using the RFC 5322 email regex\nconst rfc5322EmailSchema = z.email({ pattern: z.regexes.rfc5322Email });\n\n// Using a loose Unicode-aware email regex\nconst unicodeEmailSchema = z.email({ pattern: z.regexes.unicodeEmail });\n\ndefaultEmailSchema.parse(\"test@example.com\"); // => \"test@example.com\"\nhtml5EmailSchema.parse(\"user@domain\"); // May pass depending on regex\nrfc5322EmailSchema.parse(\"user@domain.com\");\nunicodeEmailSchema.parse(\"user@домен.com\");\n```\n\n### Return Value\nA `ZodString` schema configured for email validation, potentially with a custom regex pattern.\n```\n\n--------------------------------\n\n### Custom Email Regex Patterns with z.email()\n\nSource: https://zod.dev/v4?id=error-pretty-printing\n\nDemonstrates how to use Zod's `z.email()` API with various predefined regular expression patterns for different email validation strictness levels.\n\n```typescript\n// Zod's default email regex (Gmail rules)\n// see colinhacks.com/essays/reasonable-email-regex\nz.email(); // z.regexes.email\n```\n\n```typescript\n// the regex used by browsers to validate input[type=email] fields\n// https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/input/email\nz.email({ pattern: z.regexes.html5Email });\n```\n\n```typescript\n// the classic emailregex.com regex (RFC 5322)\nz.email({ pattern: z.regexes.rfc5322Email });\n```\n\n```typescript\n// a loose regex that allows Unicode (good for intl emails)\nz.email({ pattern: z.regexes.unicodeEmail });\n```\n\n--------------------------------\n\n### Create Template Literal Schemas with z.templateLiteral()\n\nSource: https://zod.dev/v4?id=internationalization\n\nDefine complex string patterns using z.templateLiteral() by combining literal strings and other Zod schemas, enforcing refinements like min and max.\n\n```typescript\nconst hello = z.templateLiteral([\"hello, \", z.string()]);\n// `hello, ${string}`\n \nconst cssUnits = z.enum([\"px\", \"em\", \"rem\", \"%\"]);\nconst css = z.templateLiteral([z.number(), cssUnits]);\n// `${number}px` | `${number}em` | `${number}rem` | `${number}%`\n \nconst email = z.templateLiteral([\n  z.string().min(1),\n  \"@\",\n  z.string().max(64),\n]);\n// `${string}@${string}` (the min/max refinements are enforced!)\n```\n\n### z.object() > deprecates .strip()\n\nSource: https://zod.dev/v4/changelog?id=drops-ctxpath\n\nThe `.strip()` method on `z.object()` has been deprecated in Zod 4 because it was redundant, as stripping unknown keys was already the default behavior of `z.object()`. To convert a strict object to a regular one, users can now use `z.object(A.shape)`."}}],"isError":false}}},"hookAdditionalContexts":[],"toolCallId":"tool_bac50dec-224b-467c-843e-246da169f22","startedAtMs":"1782957371557","completedAtMs":"1782957376923"},"model_call_id":"5977d0c1-3ad5-42be-85f2-1e8828435224-14-n2fk","session_id":"6573c6ff-6012-4c40-8cb2-1911b390dd96","timestamp_ms":1782957376890}
{"type":"tool_call","subtype":"completed","call_id":"tool_e6599260-5f38-4f01-b069-963ed80f698","tool_call":{"mcpToolCall":{"args":{"name":"context7-query-docs","args":{"libraryId":"/mholt/papaparse","query":"Papa.parse step streaming File complete header skipEmptyLines"},"toolCallId":"tool_e6599260-5f38-4f01-b069-963ed80f698","providerIdentifier":"context7","toolName":"query-docs","smartModeApprovalOnly":false,"skipApproval":false},"result":{"success":{"content":[{"text":{"text":"### Papa.parse - Parse Local File\n\nSource: https://context7.com/mholt/papaparse/llms.txt\n\nParses a File object from a file input element. Use 'complete' for final results, 'error' for errors, and 'step' for streaming large files row-by-row. Options like 'header', 'dynamicTyping', and 'skipEmptyLines' are supported.\n\n```javascript\n// HTML: <input type=\"file\" id=\"csvFile\">\ndocument.getElementById('csvFile').addEventListener('change', function(e) {\n  const file = e.target.files[0];\n\n  Papa.parse(file, {\n    header: true,\n    dynamicTyping: true,\n    skipEmptyLines: true,\n    complete: function(results, file) {\n      console.log(\"Parsing complete!\");\n      console.log(\"Rows parsed:\", results.data.length);\n      console.log(\"Errors:\", results.errors);\n      console.log(\"First row:\", results.data[0]);\n    },\n    error: function(error, file) {\n      console.error(\"Error reading file:\", error);\n    }\n  });\n});\n```\n\n```javascript\n// Stream large files row-by-row to avoid memory issues\nPapa.parse(largeFile, {\n  header: true,\n  step: function(results, parser) {\n    // Process one row at a time\n    console.log(\"Row:\", results.data);\n\n    // Pause parsing if needed\n    if (shouldPause) {\n      parser.pause();\n      setTimeout(() => parser.resume(), 1000);\n    }\n\n    // Abort parsing early if needed\n    if (shouldStop) {\n      parser.abort();\n    }\n  },\n  complete: function() {\n    console.log(\"All rows processed\");\n  }\n});\n```\n\n--------------------------------\n\n### Papa.parse - Parse Local File\n\nSource: https://context7.com/mholt/papaparse/llms.txt\n\nParses a File object asynchronously, supporting streaming for large files.\n\n```APIDOC\n## Papa.parse (File)\n\n### Description\nParses a File object from a file input element asynchronously. Results are delivered via callbacks.\n\n### Parameters\n#### Request Body\n- **file** (File) - Required - The File object to parse.\n- **config** (object) - Required - Configuration object including callbacks like `complete`, `error`, and `step` for streaming.\n\n### Response\n#### Success Response (200)\n- **results** (object) - Contains parsed data, errors, and metadata.\n- **file** (File) - The original file object.\n```\n\n--------------------------------\n\n### Node.js Streaming with Duplex Streams\n\nSource: https://context7.com/mholt/papaparse/llms.txt\n\nIntegrate Papa Parse with Node.js stream ecosystem for processing CSV data from various sources. This enables piping CSV data through the parsing pipeline.\n\n```javascript\nconst Papa = require('papaparse');\nconst fs = require('fs');\n\n// Create a duplex stream for parsing\nconst parseStream = Papa.parse(Papa.NODE_STREAM_INPUT, {\n  header: true,\n  dynamicTyping: true\n});\n\n// Pipe file through parser\nfs.createReadStream('data.csv')\n  .pipe(parseStream)\n  .on('data', (row) => {\n    console.log('Parsed row:', row);\n  })\n  .on('end', () => {\n    console.log('Finished parsing');\n  })\n  .on('error', (err) => {\n    console.error('Parse error:', err);\n  });\n\n// Parse readable stream directly\nconst readableStream = fs.createReadStream('large-file.csv');\nPapa.parse(readableStream, {\n  header: true,\n  step: function(results) {\n    console.log('Row:', results.data);\n  },\n  complete: function() {\n    console.log('Stream parsing complete');\n  }\n});\n```\n\n--------------------------------\n\n### Define a step callback for streaming\n\nSource: https://github.com/mholt/papaparse/blob/master/docs/docs.html\n\nUse the step callback to process rows individually during streaming, which is essential for handling large files without crashing the browser.\n\n```javascript\nstep: function(results, parser) {\n\tconsole.log(\"Row data:\", results.data);\n\tconsole.log(\"Row errors:\", results.errors);\n}\n```\n\n### Papa Parse > Streaming\n\nSource: https://github.com/mholt/papaparse/blob/master/docs/index.html\n\nFor extremely large files, Papa Parse supports streaming to avoid memory issues. By specifying a `step` callback, you can receive and process the data row-by-row. This prevents the entire file from being loaded into memory, thus avoiding browser crashes."}}],"isError":false}}},"hookAdditionalContexts":[],"toolCallId":"tool_e6599260-5f38-4f01-b069-963ed80f698","startedAtMs":"1782957371868","completedAtMs":"1782957378711"},"model_call_id":"5977d0c1-3ad5-42be-85f2-1e8828435224-14-n2fk","session_id":"6573c6ff-6012-4c40-8cb2-1911b390dd96","timestamp_ms":1782957378697}
